ce:section.ce:para:
According to the analyses of phase composition and microstructure above, the mechanism of high-dispersion CC strengthen the chloride binding ability of cement composites primarily through two pathways (Fig. 13
                        ): (1) CC with the higher specific surface area can provide more extra nucleation sites to promote the cement hydration; (2) CC with high dispersity is more conducive to exerting their inherent chloride adsorption capacity. Specifically, in terms of the nucleation sites, the documented studies have disclosed that nanoscale materials have the nucleation effect because the nucleation energy of hydration products on their surface is lower than in the pore solution [56]. This results in the promotion of cement hydration to produce more C–S–H gels. Meanwhile, the combination of CLDH and CDs alleviate the aggregation defect of CLDH, thus conferring higher dispersity and specific surface area on CC. According to the NAD analyses, the S
                        BET of CC (29.351 m2 g−1) markedly increases by 166.42 % than that of CLDH (11.017 m2 g−1). The previous work has envidenced that higher specific surface area contributes to providing more extra nucleation sites [57]. Therefore, CC can more effectively provide nucleation sites to facilitate cement hydration, thus accelerating the generaton of C–S–H gels. Due to the fact that C–S–H gels dominate the physical adsorption, CC can noticeably strengthen the physical adsorption capacity of cement pastes, and the enhancement effect is better than CLDH.
